"Explicit wait has a default polling time of 500 milliseconds,
implicit wait does not have a defined polling interval,
and fluent wait allows custom polling."

1️⃣ Implicit Wait

👉 Applies globally to all elements

driver.manage().timeouts().implicitlyWait(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
🔍 How it works:
Selenium waits up to 10 seconds
If element is found earlier → continues immediately
✅ Use Case:
Basic synchronization
⚠️ Disadvantage:
Applies to all elements (not flexible)

2️⃣ Explicit Wait (Most Important ⭐)

👉 Waits for a specific condition
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));
WebElement element = wait.until(
    ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("login"))
);
🔸 Common Conditions
1. Element Visible
wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOf(element));
2. Element Clickable
wait.until(ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.id("btn")));
3. Element Present
wait.until(ExpectedConditions.    (By.id("field")));
✅ Use Case:
Dynamic elements
Buttons, popups, loaders

3️⃣ Fluent Wait (Advanced)

👉 Like explicit wait but with more control

Wait<WebDriver> wait = new FluentWait<>(driver)
    .withTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
    .pollingEvery(Duration.ofSeconds(2))
    .ignoring(NoSuchElementException.class);

WebElement element = wait.until(
    driver -> driver.findElement(By.id("login"))
);
🔍 Features:
Custom polling time
Ignore specific exceptions

🔹 Real-Time Example
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));
// Wait until button is clickable
WebElement btn = wait.until(
    ExpectedConditions.elementToBeClickable(By.id("submit"))
);
btn.click();

In Selenium, polling time means:
👉 “How frequently Selenium checks for the element or condition”

🔹 1. Implicit Wait – Default Polling Time
👉 Polling interval is not officially defined (internal)

Selenium internally keeps checking for the element
It continuously tries until timeout is reached
👉 You can say in interview:
"Implicit wait keeps polling the DOM continuously until the element is found or timeout occurs."

🔹 2. Explicit Wait – Default Polling Time

👉 Default polling interval is:

⏱️ 500 milliseconds (0.5 seconds)
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, Duration.ofSeconds(10));

👉 Internally:

Checks condition every 500 ms
Stops when condition is satisfied or timeout reached

🔹 3. Fluent Wait – Custom Polling
👉 You can define your own polling time:

Wait<WebDriver> wait = new FluentWait<>(driver)
    .withTimeout(Duration.ofSeconds(10))
    .pollingEvery(Duration.ofSeconds(2));

👉 Here:
Checks every 2 seconds
